---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import CTABlock from '../../components/CTABlock.astro';
import { business, BASE } from '../../data/business';
import { postBySlug } from '../../data/posts';

const post = postBySlug('decking-cost-east-ayrshire-2026')!;
const siteUrl = business.siteUrl.replace(/\/$/, '');
const url = `${siteUrl}/blog/${post.slug}/`;
const ogImage = `${siteUrl}${post.ogImage}`;

const articleSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  '@id': `${url}#article`,
  headline: post.title,
  description: post.description,
  inLanguage: 'en-GB',
  datePublished: post.date,
  dateModified: post.date,
  author: {
    '@type': 'Person',
    name: post.author,
    worksFor: { '@id': `${siteUrl}/#business` },
  },
  publisher: { '@id': `${siteUrl}/#business` },
  image: [ogImage],
  mainEntityOfPage: url,
  articleSection: 'Decking',
  keywords: [post.keyword, 'composite decking Kilmarnock', 'deck builder Cumnock', 'decking cost per m2 Ayrshire', 'timber deck East Ayrshire'],
  wordCount: post.wordCount,
  about: [
    { '@type': 'Place', name: 'East Ayrshire, Scotland' },
    { '@type': 'Place', name: 'Kilmarnock, Scotland' },
    { '@type': 'Place', name: 'Cumnock, Scotland' },
  ],
};
---
<BaseLayout
  title={`${post.title} | Sorn Handyman Services`}
  description={post.description}
  canonicalPath={`/blog/${post.slug}/`}
  ogImage={ogImage}
  extraSchema={articleSchema}
>
  <Breadcrumbs trail={[
    { name: 'Home', href: `${BASE}/` },
    { name: 'Blog', href: `${BASE}/blog/` },
    { name: post.title },
  ]} />

  <article class="container-x py-10 lg:py-14 max-w-3xl">
    <header>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-amber-600">
        <span>{post.area}</span>
        <span aria-hidden class="text-navy-900/20">·</span>
        <span class="text-navy-900/60">{post.readMinutes} min read</span>
        <span aria-hidden class="text-navy-900/20">·</span>
        <time datetime={post.date} class="text-navy-900/60">{post.dateDisplay}</time>
      </div>
      <h1 class="mt-4 font-serif text-4xl md:text-5xl font-black text-navy-900 leading-tight">
        {post.title}
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-5 text-lg text-navy-900/75">
        Honest 2026 pricing for decks across East Ayrshire — pressure-treated
        softwood at £110–£160/m² supply-and-fit, composite at £180–£260/m²,
        what is actually in that number, and the permission line most folk
        do not realise exists at 30cm off the ground.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="prose-sorn mt-8 text-lg">
      <p>
        We build decks across East Ayrshire all year — mostly
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/kilmarnock/`}>Kilmarnock</a>,
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/cumnock/`}>Cumnock</a>,
        <a href={`${BASE}/areas/galston/`}>Galston</a> and the newer estates
        off the Ayr Road. If you are looking for a price, the internet
        tends to give you either a 2018 number or a London number. Neither
        helps you in KA5. This is what a proper
        <a href={`${BASE}/services/deck-building/`}>deck build</a> actually
        costs up here in 2026.
      </p>

      <h2>Pressure-treated softwood — £110 to £160 per m² fitted</h2>
      <p>
        Pressure-treated softwood (Scandinavian pine, tanalised, 32mm
        reeded deck board) is the workhorse. Fitted properly, expect
        £110 to £160 per m² including everything — substructure, fixings,
        finish. A typical 20m² back-garden deck in a Cumnock or Mauchline
        new-build lands around £2,400 to £3,000 fitted.
      </p>
      <p>Inside that price:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Excavation of the base area and disposal.</li>
        <li>Concrete pads or adjustable pedestals under every joist intersection.</li>
        <li>100×50 pressure-treated C24 joists at 400mm centres (300mm for composite — see below).</li>
        <li>Weed membrane underneath.</li>
        <li>32mm softwood deck boards, reeded top, fixed with stainless decking screws.</li>
        <li>Perimeter trim board and end caps.</li>
        <li>One coat of decking oil or stain in your chosen colour.</li>
        <li>All offcuts, packaging and old deck removed.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Lifespan on a properly-built softwood deck in an Ayrshire climate
        is eight to twelve years before boards start to cup or soften. Oil
        it every other spring and you will get to the upper end. Ignore
        it and you will not.
      </p>

      <h2>Composite — £180 to £260 per m² fitted</h2>
      <p>
        Composite (WPC — wood-plastic composite) is the big upgrade.
        Brands vary — we tend to recommend mid-tier co-extruded boards
        over bargain capped or uncapped — and pricing reflects that.
        Expect £180 to £260 per m² fitted. Same 20m² deck in composite
        is £3,800 to £5,200 fitted.
      </p>
      <p>
        Why the extra? Three real reasons:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Board cost.</strong> Composite boards are four to six
          times the price of softwood per linear metre.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Denser substructure.</strong> Composite needs joists at
          300mm centres (sometimes 250mm for thinner boards), so the
          timber cost of the cage is higher too.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Hidden fixings.</strong> Most composite is clip-fixed from
          the edges rather than face-screwed. Slower to install, cleaner
          finish.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        What you get back is a deck that does not need oiling, does not
        splinter, stays close to its fitted colour for fifteen to twenty-five
        years, and washes clean with a soft brush. Composite is genuinely
        the right call if you want a fit-and-forget surface, especially in
        an exposed garden like Muirkirk or the Galston back estates where
        weather does the most damage.
      </p>

      <h2>What is <em>not</em> included</h2>
      <p>
        Two big ones customers do not always realise are extras:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Balustrading.</strong> Spindles, posts and rails or glass
          panels add £80 to £220 per linear metre depending on spec. On a
          deck that has steps or stands more than 600mm off the ground,
          balustrade is compulsory under building regs and we will say so
          up front.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Steps and landings.</strong> Usually £150 to £300 per
          step depending on width and material. A three-step run-down to
          the lawn in softwood is roughly £500 extra; the same in composite
          is £700 plus.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Permissions above 30cm.</strong> If the finished deck
          surface sits more than 30cm above ground level at any point, you
          may need planning permission and a building warrant. Under
          Scottish permitted-development rules, decks up to 30cm high and
          covering less than 50% of the garden area are generally exempt,
          but the rules have nuances around conservation areas and listed
          buildings. In Cumnock, Mauchline, Maybole and parts of
          Kilmarnock town centre this matters. We will flag it before we
          quote and help you apply if needed — the council fee is about
          £200 and takes three to six weeks.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Electrics.</strong> LED step lights are optional — £200
          to £450 installed on a plug-in low-voltage setup. Anything
          hardwired into the house needs a Part P electrician; we will
          coordinate.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Privacy screens, pergolas and garden rooms.</strong>
          Separate trade category. Happy to bundle, but they price
          separately.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>2026 timber price context</h2>
      <p>
        A quick note on timber prices because it shapes what you are seeing
        in quotes right now. Scandinavian softwood prices softened through
        2024 and early 2025 after the post-COVID peak, then edged up
        steadily through late 2025 on the back of shipping and kiln-fuel
        costs [UNVERIFIED — confirmed via yard quotes; not from a national
        index]. For our yards in Ayrshire that means softwood deck board
        is about 10–12% higher than this time last year, while composite
        has been roughly flat because the plastic component moved the
        opposite way. Bottom line: softwood is closer to composite on
        whole-life cost than it used to be. Worth factoring in.
      </p>

      <h2>What we bring to the build</h2>
      <p>
        A proper substructure is where decks live or die. We excavate
        to a clean sub-base, pour concrete pads for every post upright
        where the ground is soft, and use galvanised post shoes to keep
        timber off wet soil. Joists are C24 grade, ventilated with an
        air-gap from the boards, and every screw is stainless. That
        sounds basic — it is — but it is the difference between a deck
        that lasts ten years and one that sinks a corner after two
        winters.
      </p>

      <h2>FAQ</h2>

      <h3>How long does a 20m² deck take to build?</h3>
      <p>
        Softwood — three to four working days for a two-person crew.
        Composite — four to six working days. Add a day each side for
        excavation and finish.
      </p>

      <h3>Do you remove the old deck?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes. Tear-out and disposal is typically £250 to £500 on top
        depending on size and whether the sub-base is reusable. We pay
        the skip fee.
      </p>

      <h3>What time of year is best to build?</h3>
      <p>
        Late March to early October. Winter builds are possible on
        composite (it does not need to dry before finishing) but
        ground conditions are harder and we charge the same — there is
        no weather discount.
      </p>

      <h3>Do I need a building warrant in East Ayrshire?</h3>
      <p>
        If the finished surface is 30cm or less above ground and the
        deck covers less than half the garden, generally no. Above
        that, yes — or in conservation areas regardless. We will tell
        you honestly and handle the paperwork if needed.
      </p>

      <h3>Which brand of composite do you recommend?</h3>
      <p>
        Off the record we have a shortlist we keep coming back to —
        ring us and we will talk it through with your budget. We do
        not take kickbacks from any brand; whatever we recommend is
        whatever we would fit on our own house.
      </p>

      <h3>Can you do a free site visit?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes — no call-out fee anywhere in Kilmarnock, Cumnock, Galston,
        Sorn or the rest of <a href={`${BASE}/areas/`}>our East Ayrshire patch</a>.
        Photos over WhatsApp first usually get you a ballpark without
        us even driving out.
      </p>

      <p>
        Ring Fraser or WhatsApp Aidan — we will come out this week,
        measure, and have a firm written quote back to you inside
        forty-eight hours.
      </p>

      <div class="not-prose mt-10 rounded-2xl border border-navy-900/10 bg-navy-50/50 p-6">
        <p class="text-sm text-navy-900/60">Written by</p>
        <p class="mt-1 font-serif text-xl font-bold text-navy-900">{post.author}</p>
        <p class="mt-2 text-navy-900/75 text-sm">{post.authorBio}</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <CTABlock
    heading="Thinking about a deck for summer 2026?"
    sub="Free site visit across East Ayrshire. Ring Fraser or WhatsApp Aidan a rough sketch — we’ll have a firm quote back inside 48 hours."
    location="East Ayrshire"
  />
</BaseLayout>
